        "text": "Solar panels do add value in Brisbane, but typically less than sellers expect. Buyers view solar as a running cost reduction rather than a premium feature, and the value attributed depends heavily on the system age, size, and condition. A new 10kW system with battery storage is meaningfully more compelling to buyers than a 1.5kW system installed in 2012. Valuers and banks often assign limited capital value to solar, so the practical benefit shows up more in buyer preference and days on market than in a headline price uplift."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What do I need to disclose about solar panels when selling in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Solar panels fixed to the roof are generally treated as fixtures and are included in the sale unless the contract specifically excludes them. You should disclose any known defects with the system, including inverter faults, panel damage, or connectivity issues. Feed-in tariff arrangements are between you and your electricity retailer and do not automatically transfer to the buyer. The buyer will need to set up their own arrangement after settlement. If you want to take the panels with you, this must be listed as an exclusion in the contract of sale."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I take my solar panels with me when I sell my home in Brisbane?",
