      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Solar Panels When Selling Your Home in Brisbane 2026
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Queensland has the highest rooftop solar uptake in the world. If your home has a system, here is what you need to know before you list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A significant proportion of homes in Brisbane's inner east now have rooftop solar installed. For sellers, this raises a set of practical questions that often do not get addressed until late in the campaign: Does the system stay with the house? What do you need to disclose? Does it actually add to the sale price? And what does the buyer need to know about the feed-in tariff? Getting clear on these questions before you list is worth doing.</p>

      <p>The good news is that solar is generally a positive factor in a Brisbane sale. Buyers in this city are familiar with solar systems and most regard them favourably. The complication is that the value buyers ascribe to solar depends significantly on the system's age, size, and condition, and sellers sometimes have inflated expectations about the uplift a solar system provides. Understanding how buyers actually think about solar helps you position it accurately in your marketing and avoid mispricing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers actually look at when they see solar</h2>
      <p>Buyers who are interested in a property with solar will typically ask a handful of specific questions. The first is the system size in kilowatts, because that determines how much of a household's electricity usage it can offset. A 6kW or 10kW system on a family home is meaningfully more attractive than a 1.5kW system that covers minimal daytime consumption. The second question is age: solar panel technology has improved considerably over the past decade, and buyers who understand solar know that older systems carry higher inverter replacement risk and may be approaching the end of their effective life.</p>

      <p>Feed-in tariff rates are another area of buyer interest. Queensland's feed-in tariff arrangements have changed significantly since the early years of high export rates. Current export rates are modest, and most buyers understand that the primary financial benefit of solar is daytime self-consumption rather than export income. If the property has battery storage, that is a legitimate differentiator and buyers with an interest in energy efficiency will respond to it.</p>

      <p>The inverter brand and condition matter more than most sellers realise. Inverters have a shorter typical lifespan than panels, and an inverter that is more than ten years old or showing fault indicators will be noted by buyers who know what they are looking at. A system serviced recently by a licensed solar technician, with a current health report available, demonstrates that the system has been maintained and gives buyers confidence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Does solar add to the sale price in Brisbane?</h2>
      <p>Yes, but the uplift is usually more modest than sellers expect. Research on solar's impact on property values in Australian cities consistently shows a positive effect, but it tends to be smaller than the system's replacement cost would suggest. Buyers treat solar as a running cost reduction rather than a premium feature. They will factor in lower electricity bills and weigh that against the estimated remaining life of the system, not against what the system cost to install.</p>

      <p>A well-maintained modern system in good condition can make your property more attractive relative to comparable listings without solar, which can matter in a competitive market where buyers are weighing multiple options. In practice, the clearest benefit of solar in a Brisbane sale is buyer preference: a buyer who is genuinely interested in two comparable homes and one has solar may prioritise that property, particularly if they have been thinking about installing solar themselves and can see it as a cost and hassle saving.</p>

      <p>Formal valuations often do not attribute substantial capital value to solar systems, which can create a disconnect between what sellers expect and what banks will lend against. If you are pricing your home in part on the basis of the solar system's value, have that expectation checked against comparable local sales before you commit to a number.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure and what stays with the house</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, solar panels fixed to the roof are generally treated as fixtures and are included in the sale unless the contract specifically lists them as excluded chattels. This is the default position, and most buyers assume the solar system is included. If you intend to take the panels with you, you need to note that in the contract and discuss it with your agent before listing, because buyers who discover it late in the process may interpret it as an attempt to mislead them.</p>

      <p>Removing panels from a roof carries practical risks: roof penetrations, voided roof warranties, and the cost of a licensed electrician to disconnect and reinstall. In most cases, the better commercial decision is to leave the system in place and position it as a feature of the property. Taking panels rarely produces a net financial benefit once the removal costs and the likely impact on buyer sentiment are accounted for.</p>

      <p>Feed-in tariff arrangements are personal agreements between you and your electricity retailer. They do not transfer automatically to the buyer. The buyer will need to contact their preferred retailer after settlement and set up their own arrangement. If you are on a legacy high feed-in tariff, it is worth being transparent with buyers that this rate will not continue for them, to avoid any misunderstanding about the financial benefit they are purchasing.</p>

      <p>Known defects in the system should be disclosed. Inverter faults, damaged panels, connectivity issues, or a system that has not been generating correctly are all matters a buyer would reasonably want to know about before exchanging contracts. Disclosure upfront avoids disputes later and demonstrates that you are dealing in good faith.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing solar as a selling feature</h2>
      <p>If your system is in good condition, presenting it well in your marketing costs very little and can make a meaningful difference to buyer interest. Have the system serviced by a licensed installer before listing and ask for a short written health summary. Print out twelve months of generation data from the monitoring app or inverter display: this shows buyers what the system actually produces in Brisbane conditions, which is more compelling than a brochure specification. Include the system size, inverter brand, panel brand, and approximate age in your property description. Buyers who care about solar will ask these questions anyway, and having the answers ready in the marketing materials demonstrates transparency.</p>

      <p>If you have battery storage, present it prominently. The proportion of Brisbane homes with battery storage is still relatively low, and buyers who have been researching the cost of adding a battery will recognise the value of finding one already installed and operational.</p>

